content: After the year-end silence, we are all becoming more active.
We will now begin with participation check.
Xespok, Before, virag, SamSite, Red_Zombie, tianxia, jamphen, Fermat, slamduk, whte, weigui, luwenzhe, scm2000, coco_yuang, Intotherenju, pengyu, guminzhao, yyfcsd, LiuJianping, sosei.
I will begin with introducing the two players of the game
in year 1991, there were two world championships held each time at the same place - one for renju, one for gomoku
the gomoku WC only happened twice
and since 1993, only renju WC was held
it was pente championship also, not?
so, while Nakamura won the renju WC in 1989 and 1991,
there was also big fight in gomoku WC same time
and Tarannikov won the gomoku WC in 1991
because the QT for Renju WC 1991 was so long before,
so I was just 16 years old,
and did not qualify for renju WC
but, since I had won the USSR gomoku championship
so I qualified for gomoku WC.
I remember, one of my game, against Tarannikov began like this
ha it is now used in china
for several years, Tarannikov was known as a gomoku player,
and renju players did not take him seriously.
there was a common thinking - any renjuplayer can beat any gomoku player
but then gomoku became very quiet sport in Russia,
and those gomoku players had to choose -
to give up playing, or switch to renju
Tarannikov and other leading players, they all switched to renju.
who is the opponent of today's game.
how about are the rule of gomoku?
in first years of renju, both Tarannikov and Fedorkin played poorly,
Very soon they started to rise in their renju career as well,
I am not good at the email WC history,
but I remember at least Fedorkin won it once before
it seems Tarannikov still in A group
later on, Tarannikov began to win several Russian renju tournaments
and even though he has no remarkable results in international renju yet,
he is surely very strong and dangerous opponent to anyone.
He also played in the QT and B-tournament in WC 2003
Today's game, was played between Tarannikov and Fedorkin in year 2000,
in the tournament in Russia, named "Soosyrv Cup"
that Cup has been played for so many years.
The tournament got the name and idea from one incident in renju tournament in Russia long ago.
Ants Soosyrv, having finished the tournament in Russia, was about to go home, to Estonia, but he had bunch of Russian money left, which he thought are useless later,
so he left them with Russian renju players.
and they decided to buy one trophy for that money
and that tournament is played every year, until now.
In year 2000, Tarannikov and Fedorking were playing famous variant of d3
This variant became especially popular after 1999,
What is the popular 10th move today?
but back in 2000, the g9 was not known yet.
Most of you have seen my 3rd and 6th game with Nakamura
and most players used that later.
13 and 14 - so natural, nothing to explain.
almost made me lost a game
and he failed to find win.
lots of renju masters studied this variant deeply
and 15-g8 as well as 15-g9 became proper variants.
how many of you have played this variant before?
I hope you will try more
I have seen analyses like this:
and if you look at the statistics of finished games,
black and white win about eqully here
then later on black will have good space on other sides.
Fedorkin surprised his opponent with this new 16th move.
I dont know if Tarannikov had analysed it before or not,
but at least for me this 16 is new.
What do you think about it?
it looks like a very good block
and white would feel difficult to develop from here.
and 3x3 threats at g11, i11, h12
at least the 4x3 threat was closed
now we need to deal with all the 3x3 traps
here it is much harder to win I guess,
but Fedorking found a nice plan.
the idea is to force 4x4 trap to i11
forcing blacks to g11 and f11
therefore black cannot block simpe to e8
also, black cannot use four first
therefore, he could only play here.
But nothing can stop from trapping that 4x4 anyway
this game rises lots of interesting questions.
Did not we say 4 is a must?
several moves need to be tested here
you can help me if you find a good one
any other move kills 3x3 threat and white VCF threat?
its like perfect position - white has always the necessary piece of attack
ok we study g11, as it is most natural move

hereby, we will end this nice lesson! We learned about great new 16th move by Fedorking, followed by wonderful 20th move. We had an opportunity to learn about Tarannikov, and something about the history of renju and gomoku, I hope you all enjoyed it.
